<article id=3D"content" role=3D"main">

<!-- #BeginEditable "Body" -->=20


<h1 class=3D"center">What is Area?</h1>=20


<p class=3D"center larger"><i>Area is the size of a surface!</i></p>=20

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<h3>Example:</h3>=20

	<p>These shapes all have the same area of 9:</p>=20
	<p class=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/geometry/images=
/area-same.svg" alt=3D"same area of 9" height=3D"192" width=3D"300"></p>=20
</div>=20

<div class=3D"center">
	<div class=3D"box" style=3D"max-width:400px;"><img src=3D"https://www.math=
sisfun.com/geometry/images/area-paint.svg" alt=3D"area paint" height=3D"112=
" width=3D"170"><br>It helps to imagine <b>how much paint</b> would cover t=
he shape.</div>
</div>





<h2>Area of Simple Shapes</h2>=20

<p>There are special formulas for certain shapes:</p>=20

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<h3>Example: What is the area of this rectangle?</h3>=20

	<p class=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/geometry/images=
/area-rectangle-3-5.svg" alt=3D"Area Count" height=3D"130" width=3D"191"></=
p>=20
	<p>The formula is:</p>=20
	<p class=3D"center"><span class=3D"larger">Area <em>=3D</em> w =C3=97 h</s=
pan><br>
w <em>=3D</em> width<br>
h <em>=3D</em> height</p>=20
	<p>The width is 5, and the height is 3, so we know <b>w <em>=3D</em> 5</b>=
 and <b>h <em>=3D</em> 3</b>:</p>=20
	<p class=3D"center larger">Area <em>=3D</em> 5 =C3=97 3 <em>=3D</em> <b>15=
</b></p>=20
</div>=20

<p>Learn more at <a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/area.html">Area of P=
lane Shapes</a>.</p>=20


<h2>Area by Counting Squares</h2>=20

<p>We can also put the shape on a grid and count the number of squares:</p>=
=20
<p class=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/geometry/images/=
area-count-a.svg" alt=3D"Area Count" height=3D"162" width=3D"242"><br>
<span class=3D"larger">The rectangle has an area of <b>15</b></span></p>=20
<p class=3D"center">Example: When each square is <b>1 meter</b> on a side, =
then the area is <b>15 m<sup>2</sup></b> (15 square meters)</p>=20


<h2>Square Meter vs Meter Square</h2>=20

<p>The basic unit of area in the metric system is the <b>square meter</b>, =
which is a square that has 1 meter on each side:</p>=20
<p class=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/measure/images/s=
quare-m.svg" alt=3D"1 Square Meter" height=3D"140" width=3D"140"><br>
<span class=3D"larger"> 1 square meter</span></p>=20
<p>Be careful to say "square meters" not "meters squared":</p>=20
<p class=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/measure/images/s=
quare-m-vs-m-square.svg" alt=3D"3 Square Meters vs 3 meters squared" height=
=3D"403" width=3D"631"></p>=20
<p>There are also "square mm", "square cm" and so on, learn more at <a href=
=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/measure/metric-area.html">Metric Area</a>.</=
p>=20
<p class=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/measure/images/s=
quare-cm.jpg" alt=3D"square cm" height=3D"120" width=3D"200"></p>=20


<h2>Approximate Area by Counting Squares</h2>=20

<p>Sometimes the squares don't match the shape exactly, but we can get an "=
approximate" answer.</p>=20

<h4>One way is:</h4>=20

<ul>=20
	<li><b>more</b> than half a square counts as <b>1</b></li>=20
	<li><b>less</b> than half a square counts as <b>0</b></li>=20
</ul>=20
<p>Like this:</p>=20
<p class=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/geometry/images/=
area-count-b.svg" alt=3D"Area Count" height=3D"189" width=3D"189"><span cla=
ss=3D"larger"><br>
This pentagon has an area of <b>approximately 17</b></span></p>=20

<h4>&nbsp;</h4>=20

<h4>Or we can count one square when the <b>areas seem to add up</b>.</h4>=
=20

<p>Example: Here the area marked "<b>4</b>" seems equal to about 1 whole sq=
uare (also for "<b>8</b>"):</p>=20
<p class=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/geometry/images/=
area-count-c.svg" alt=3D"Area Count" height=3D"162" width=3D"189"><span cla=
ss=3D"larger"><br>
This circle has an area of <b>approximately 14</b></span></p>=20

<h4>&nbsp;</h4>=20

<h4>But using a formula (when possible) is best:</h4>=20

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<h3>Example: The circle has a radius of 2,1 meters:</h3>=20

	<p class=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/geometry/images=
/area-circle.svg" alt=3D"area circle 2.1 radius" height=3D"114" width=3D"11=
4"></p>=20
	<p>The formula is:</p>=20
	<p class=3D"center"><span class=3D"larger">Area <em>=3D</em> </span><span =
class=3D"times">=CF=80</span><span class=3D"larger"> =C3=97 r<sup>2</sup></=
span></p>=20
	<p>Where:</p>=20
	<ul>=20
		<li><span class=3D"times">=CF=80</span> <em>=3D</em> the <a href=3D"https=
://www.mathsisfun.com/numbers/pi.html">number pi</a> (3,1416...)</li>=20
		<li>r <em>=3D</em> radius</li>=20
	</ul>=20
	<p>The radius is <b>2,1m</b>, so:</p>

	<div class=3D"two">
<span class=3D"lt">Area <em>=3D</em></span><span class=3D"rt"> 3,1416... =
=C3=97 (2,1m)<sup>2</sup></span>
<span class=3D"lt">=3D</span><span class=3D"rt"> 3,1416... =C3=97 (2,1m =C3=
=97 2,1m)</span>
<span class=3D"lt">=3D</span><span class=3D"rt"> 13,854... m<sup>2</sup></s=
pan>
</div>
<p>So the circle has an area of <b>13,85 square meters</b> (to 2 decimal pl=
aces)</p>=20
</div>=20


<h2>Area of Difficult Shapes</h2>=20

<p>We can sometimes break a shape up into two or more simpler shapes:</p>=
=20

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<h3>Example: What is the area of this Shape?</h3>=20

	<p class=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/geometry/images=
/area-grass.svg" alt=3D"area grass" height=3D"118" width=3D"205"></p>=20
	<p>Let's break the area into two parts:</p>=20
	<p class=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/geometry/images=
/area-grass2.svg" alt=3D"area grass zone A and B" height=3D"118" width=3D"2=
05"></p>=20
	<p>Part A is a square:</p>=20
	<div class=3D"so">Area of A <em>=3D</em> a<sup>2</sup> <em>=3D</em> 20m =
=C3=97 20m <em>=3D</em> 400m<sup>2</sup></div>
<p>Part B is a triangle. Viewed sideways it has a base of 20m and a height =
of 14m.</p>=20
<div class=3D"so">Area of B <em>=3D</em> =C2=BDb =C3=97 h <em>=3D</em> =C2=
=BD =C3=97 20m =C3=97 14m <em>=3D</em> 140m<sup>2</sup></div>
<p>So the total area is:</p>=20
<div>=20
<p class=3D"so">Area <em>=3D</em> Area of A + Area of B</p>=20
<p class=3D"so">Area <em>=3D</em> 400m<sup>2</sup> + 140m<sup>2</sup></p>=
=20
<p class=3D"so">Area <em>=3D</em> 540m<sup>2</sup></p>=20
</div>=20

</div>=20


<h2>Area by Adding Up Triangles</h2>=20

<div class=3D"center80">=20
<p>We can also break up a shape into <a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/=
triangle.html">triangles</a>:</p>=20
<p class=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/geometry/images/=
area-3-triangles.svg" alt=3D"area 3 triangles" height=3D"145" width=3D"207"=
></p>=20
<p>Then measure the base (<b>b</b>) and height (<b>h</b>) of each triangle:=
</p>=20
<p class=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/geometry/images/=
area-3-triangles-b.svg" alt=3D"area 3 triangles with base and height" heigh=
t=3D"173" width=3D"359"></p>=20
<p>Then calculate each area (using <span class=3D"larger">Area <em>=3D</em>=
 =C2=BDb =C3=97 h</span>) and add them all up.</p>

</div>=20

<div class=3D"gap"></div>
<p class=3D"floatRt"><a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/geometry/area-po=
lygon-drawing.html"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/geometry/images/=
area-irregular-polygon2.gif" alt=3D"area irregular polygon" height=3D"258" =
width=3D"295"></a></p>=20


<h2>Area by Coordinates</h2>=20

<p>When we know the coordinates of each corner point we can use the <a href=
=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/geometry/area-irregular-polygons.html">Area =
of Irregular Polygons</a> method.</p>=20
<p>There is an <a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/geometry/area-polygon-=
drawing.html">Area of a Polygon by Drawing Tool</a> that can help too.</p>

